=== Overview ===
It is located at the southwest edge of the Hozu ring-moat settlement. Although the current site belongs to former {{ill|lt=Tōichi District|Q11405036|qid=Q11405036|1=Toichi district}}, before the {{ill|lt=early modern period|Q5308718|qid=Q5308718|1=Early modern period}} it is said to have been in Ita-shiki, about 300 m east of the present location, and moved here along with relocation of the Hozu settlement. In ancient times, the Hozu clan of Mononobe surname is said to have lived in the ring-moat settlement, and this shrine is inferred to have worshiped their ancestral deity.

=== Precinct ===
The honden consists of two buildings, north and south honden. The south honden was built in the rare "sumiki-iri {{ill|lt=kasuga-zukuri|Q3193781|qid=Q3193781|1=Kasuga-zukuri}}" method during the {{ill|lt=Bunka (era)|Q1373146|qid=Q1373146|lt=Bunka|1=Bunka}} years (1804-1818).

=== Local information ===
; Location
*{{ill|lt=Nara Prefecture|Q131287|qid=Q131287|1=Nara Prefecture}}{{ill|lt=Shiki District|Q1155036|qid=Q1155036|1=Shiki District, Nara}}{{ill|lt=Tawaramoto|Q1203159|qid=Q1203159|1=Tawaramoto, Nara}}Hozu 150

; Access
* About 10 minutes on foot west from {{ill|lt=Tawaramoto Station|Q7689224|qid=Q7689224|1=Tawaramoto Station}} on the {{ill|lt=Kintetsu|Q1531085|qid=Q1531085|lt=Kintetsu|1=Kintetsu Railway}} {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Kashihara Line|1=UNKNOWN}}

